<h3>Miscellaneous Personal Stuff</h3>

Follow me on Twitter at <a
href="http://www.twitter.com/thcormen">@thcormen</a>.  You can also
read about me on <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cormen">Wikipedia</a>.  (Note: I
did not create this entry, nor have I edited it.)  I'm even listed
among "Noted residents, past and present" in the <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oceanside,_New_York">Wikipedia page
on Oceanside, NY</a>.  (Nor did I edit this page.)

<p>

My wife, Nicole, and I took a <a href="bbqtour">Barbecue tour</a> of
the South in August 1998.

<p>

In July 2010, I rollerbladed the <a
href="http://friendsofcdatrails.org/CdA_Trail/index.html">Trail of the
Coeur D'Alenes</a>, a 71.4-mile-long paved rail trail in the Idaho
panhandle.  Accompanied by my friend, Paul Daro, who also bladed, and
Nicole, who biked, we went 42 miles the first day and the balance the
second day.  Here is a <a href="images/Plummer.jpg">photo</a> of the
three of us at the start of the first day, at the western trailhead in
Plummer, Idaho, (on the Coeur D'Alene reservation) and here is a <a
href="images/Mullan.jpg">photo</a> of Paul and me at the start of the
second day, at the eastern trailhead in Mullan, Idaho.  We met <a
href="images/CDA-moose.jpg">this fellow</a> on the trail during the
first day.  <a href="CDA.html">This page</a> has some rough videos
that Paul took.

<p>

My brother-in-law, Tony Pecora, is the first patient in the US to
undergo the Edmonton Protocol for treatment of juvenile diabetes.
Check out his website at <a
href="http://www.isletsupporter.com">http://www.isletsupporter.com</a>.

<p>

I was the Ice Man for the <a href="http://www.mdbbq.com">Maryland
State Barbecue Championship</a> in 2003, 2004, and 2005.  Here's a <a
href="ICE.jpg">photo</a> from the 2005 contest of me with a
quad-runner full of 40-pound bags of ice.  The photo was taken by the
<a href="http://www.dizzypigbbq.com/">Dizzy Pigs</a>, the 2005 and
2006 Grand Champions.  Even with the megaphone, I was pretty hoarse by
the end of the second day.  The Dizzy Pigs, and all the other
contestants, can explain why.

<p>

I was <a href="http://www.kcbs.us">Kansas City Barbeque Society</a>
Certified Barbeque Judge number 62145.  (I have purposely let my KCBS
membership lapse.)  My first contest as a certified judge was the 2011
Maryland State Championship in Bel Air.  <a
href="images/Judging%20chicken.JPG">Here</a> is a photo of me just
starting to judge the first item, chicken.  And <a
href="images/After%20judging.JPG">here</a> is a photo after judging
five entries each of chicken, pork ribs, pork, and beef brisket.
(Photos courtesy of Craig Ward, a.k.a. "Mr. Time To Go," a.k.a. "Large
And In Charge," the contest organizer.)

<p>

In September 1997, Nicole and I finished hiking all 48 of the
4000-foot peaks in the <a href="http://hikethewhites.com/">White
Mountains</a> of New Hampshire.

<p>

A former student wrote an article for USA Hockey about the time I was
"<a href="http://www.usahockey.com/Adult/Features/ThatGuy.aspx">that
guy</a>."  (The photo in the article is not of me.  Goalies have all
their teeth.)

